political decisions were viewed as gender transgressions by the state, the public, and even the burgeoning women’s movement, which considered violence as patriarchal and unfeminist. Death in the Shape of a Young Girl questions this separation of political violence from feminist politics and offers a new understanding of left-wing female terrorists’ actions as feminist practices that challenged existing gender ideologies. Patricia Melzer draws on archival sources, unpublished letters, and interviews with former activists to paint a fresh and interdisciplinary picture of West Germany’s most notorious political group, from feminist responses to sexist media coverage of female terrorists to the gendered nature of their infamous hunger strikes while in prison. Placing the controversial actions of the Red Army Faction into the context of feminist politics, Death in the Shape of a Young Girl offers an innovative and engaging cultural history that foregrounds how gender shapes our perception of women’s political choices and of any kind of political violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical violencexHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aPolitical violencezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen political activistsxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aWomen political activistszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen revolutionariesxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aWomen revolutionarieszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen terroristsxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aWomen terroristszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.